          {
            "heading": "Silence is not consent",
            "text": "In higher **power distance** settings, disagreeing with a senior leader in public can feel disrespectful, so agreement in the room may be **deference**, not genuine buy-in. If you lead like a US-default manager — 'I floated it, nobody objected, so we're aligned' — you will repeatedly mistake silence for consent and get surprised at execution time.\n\nYour job is to build channels where dissent can travel safely. That means not relying on the open-floor challenge that works with your US CSMs to be the only way input reaches you."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Engineering dissent into the process",
            "text": "To **surface dissent** from higher-power-distance teams, change the mechanics, not just the invitation. Ask for input in writing before the meeting, solicit views privately or through the team lead, call on people by name for their specific area, and separate idea-generation from your own stated opinion so you don't anchor the room. Leaving your view unstated until the end keeps you from accidentally closing the discussion.\n\nSmall structural moves outperform 'please speak freely,' which asks people to violate a norm on the spot in front of their peers and their boss."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Two decision styles",
            "text": "Cultures differ not only in hierarchy but in how decisions get made once discussion ends. Some lean **consensus**, where the group grinds toward alignment before committing and the decision is then stable. Others lean **top-down**, where a leader decides quickly and the decision can still be revisited. These can combine surprisingly: a culture can be hierarchical yet consensus-oriented.\n\nName the style you're using. When you partner across US, Manila, and China lines, mismatched expectations about who decides and whether a decision is final cause more thrash than the decision itself."
          }
