        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Right Message, Right Channel",
            "text": "Async communication breaks down when everything lands in one undifferentiated stream. **Channel discipline** means matching each message to a channel by two dimensions: how urgent it is and how permanent it needs to be. A quick clarification fits a chat thread; a decision or policy that people will reference for months belongs in a durable document, not buried in scrollback.\n\nWhen you mix these up — putting a lasting decision in a fast-moving chat, or paging someone for something that could wait — you either lose important information or you burn goodwill with false urgency. Deciding the channel is part of the message."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Write So No One Has to Ask a Follow-Up",
            "text": "In a room, an ambiguous request gets fixed instantly by the puzzled look on someone's face. Across distance, ambiguity costs a full cycle of back-and-forth — and with a night-shift team, a badly worded ask can stall real work. A **self-contained message** carries its own context: what you need, why, by when, and what 'done' looks like, so the reader can act without a follow-up question.\n\nThe test is simple: could someone who missed all prior context act correctly on this message alone? If not, add the missing context before you send it. Good async writing front-loads clarity so the reader spends effort acting, not decoding."
          },
          {
            "heading": "One Source of Truth, Known Response Times",
            "text": "Distributed teams waste enormous energy hunting for the current version of a number, a policy, or a status. A **single source of truth** — one agreed place where the authoritative version of a thing lives — kills that waste and prevents people acting on stale information. If your billing SOP or a churn dashboard exists in three slightly different copies, someone will act on the wrong one.\n\nPair that with explicit **response-time expectations**: state what counts as urgent versus what can wait a shift, so people aren't anxiously watching chat or, conversely, sitting on something you needed fast. Clear norms let people fully disconnect when off, which directly reduces the night-shift toll."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Turn Meetings Into Documents",
            "text": "**Meeting-to-doc conversion** is the habit of asking, for any proposed meeting, whether its output could instead be a written document people read and comment on asynchronously. Status updates, information sharing, and simple approvals almost always can. What resists conversion is genuine two-way work: debate, negotiation, coaching, and relationship-building.\n\nConverting the convertible meetings does two things at once. It gives your Manila team back hours of their night they were spending listening passively, and it produces a durable artifact others can reference later — feeding your single source of truth instead of vanishing when the call ends."
          }
        ],
