        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Two Kinds of Trust",
            "text": "Distributed teams rely on two different things people both call trust. The first is competence trust: believing a colleague will deliver quality work. The second is relational trust: believing they have your back and won't punish honesty. Both are harder to build without the casual moments a shared office provides.\n\nAt the start of a new working relationship you often lean on **swift trust** — an initial, provisional trust extended based on roles and reputation before it's been earned through experience. Swift trust lets a distributed team start moving immediately, but it is fragile; it must be quickly reinforced by real, reliable follow-through or it collapses."
          },
          {
            "heading": "The Trust Battery",
            "text": "Picture each working relationship as a **trust battery** that charges with every kept promise and drains with every missed one, every surprise, every ignored message. Across distance the battery drains faster, because you have fewer positive interactions to recharge it and small negatives loom larger without context.\n\nThe practical implication: reliability is the currency of distributed leadership. Doing what you said, when you said, in the channel you agreed, quietly recharges trust across your whole org. Chronic small misses — a promised answer that never comes, a decision reversed without explanation — drain it faster than any single dramatic failure."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Assume Positive Intent",
            "text": "When a message is terse or a task is late and you can't see the person, your brain fills the silence with a story — usually an unflattering one. Left unchecked this becomes corrosive, especially across cultures where directness, silence, and deference carry different meanings. **Assume positive intent** is the deliberate discipline of choosing the most generous plausible explanation before you react.\n\nThis is not naivety; it is a bias-correction. A blunt reply from a China partner or a quiet response from a Manila teammate may reflect a night shift, a language boundary, or a cultural norm — not disrespect. Asking a clarifying question instead of assuming the worst prevents most distributed conflicts before they start."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Safety Without Standing Over People",
            "text": "**Psychological safety** — the shared belief that you can speak up, admit a mistake, or disagree without being punished — is the soil everything else grows in, and it is easily undermined at a distance where people can't read your tone. On a team spanning US, Manila, and China hierarchies, junior or deferential members may stay silent unless you actively invite dissent and reward honesty when it appears.\n\nThe balancing act is **presence without surveillance**: being visibly available, responsive, and interested without monitoring keystrokes or demanding constant check-ins. Presence says 'I'm here and I care'; surveillance says 'I don't trust you.' The first builds the battery; the second drains it while pretending to protect it."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "A quiet CSM and a wrong story",
          "text": "A CSM on the Manila SMB team goes quiet for two shifts on a churn-risk account you flagged. Your first instinct writes an unflattering story: they're avoiding it. Practicing **assume positive intent**, you send a genuine question instead of a reprimand and learn they were blocked waiting on a billing answer that never came — a drain on their **trust battery**, not negligence. By unblocking it and thanking them for surfacing it, you reinforce **psychological safety**: honesty about being stuck is safe here. Had you led with suspicion, you'd have modeled **surveillance**, taught the team to hide blockers, and drained trust across the group."
        },
