        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Connection Has to Be Engineered",
            "text": "In an office, relationships form for free in hallways and at lunch. On a distributed team, connection that isn't designed simply doesn't happen, and people slide into pure transactional contact. **Intentional connection** is the deliberate creation of the human moments an office would have produced by accident — a few minutes of non-work conversation, celebrating wins by name, one-on-ones that aren't only status.\n\nThis isn't soft filler. Weak ties raise **isolation risk**, and isolated people disengage, hide problems, and eventually leave. A small, consistent investment in connection is what keeps a high-functioning distributed team from becoming a group of strangers who happen to share a queue."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Guard Against Always-On Creep",
            "text": "When work is digital and teams span time zones, the boundary of the workday blurs and **always-on creep** sets in — a slow expectation that people are reachable at any hour. For your Manila team already carrying the night-shift toll, this is how you burn out your best people while believing you're just being responsive.\n\nProtecting energy is a leadership duty, not a perk. Model boundaries yourself: don't expect instant replies outside agreed hours, be explicit that an off-hours message isn't an emergency, and respect rest as non-negotiable. Sustainable performance beats a burst of heroics followed by attrition, and on a distributed team the manager sets the ceiling on how hard the always-on pressure squeezes."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Beware Proximity Bias",
            "text": "**Proximity bias** is the unconscious tendency to favor the people you interact with most — usually those closest to your time zone or the ones you happen to see live — when handing out opportunities, credit, and attention. On your org it quietly advantages US staff over the Manila teams and undervalues China partners you meet less often.\n\nLeft unchecked, proximity bias corrodes fairness and drives your distant talent to disengage. Counter it deliberately: track who gets the visible projects and the public credit, rotate high-value opportunities across locations, and make sure recognition reaches the people you don't see, not just the ones on your screen most."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Build Belonging Across Cultures",
            "text": "**Inclusion across distance** means every member feels their contribution matters regardless of location, seniority, or culture. It's the difference between a team with one dominant center and a few satellites, and a genuinely shared team. Rotating meeting times so the same region isn't always inconvenienced, sourcing input from quieter members in writing, and crediting work publicly across locations all build it.\n\nThis is where the whole course compounds. Async discipline, trust, and outcome accountability only produce lasting results if people feel they belong enough to stay and bring their full effort. Sustainable distributed performance is trust and connection, maintained deliberately, over years."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "Catching a proximity-bias drift",
          "text": "Reviewing who presented in the last few executive reporting cycles, you notice the visible customer-story slots keep going to your US MidMarket team while your Manila SMB CSMs — who drive strong outcomes — stay invisible. That's **proximity bias** quietly at work. You correct it by rotating a Manila CSM into the next exec readout and crediting their retention win by name, an act of **inclusion across distance**. At the same time you notice your night-shift leads answering off-hours pings, so you publicly reset the norm to curb **always-on creep**. Both moves protect the **intentional connection** and belonging that keep your best distributed people engaged."
        },
