        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Make feedback specific and behavioral",
            "text": "Vague feedback — 'be more strategic,' 'own it more' — is unusable because the person can't tell what to change. **Behavioral feedback** names the specific action and its effect. A clean structure is **Situation-Behavior-Impact (SBI)**: 'In the exec readout (situation), you presented churn without a recommendation (behavior), so leadership couldn't act and it looked reactive (impact).'\n\nSBI keeps you on observable facts, not character verdicts. 'You presented without a recommendation' is coachable; 'you're not strategic' is a label that invites defensiveness and gives no path forward."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Frequency beats intensity",
            "text": "The biggest feedback failure isn't harshness — it's saving it up. Rare, high-stakes feedback lands as a verdict; frequent, low-stakes feedback lands as coaching. **Feedback frequency** matters more than polish: small, timely corrections in the flow of work are easier to hear and act on than a quarterly pile-up.\n\nWhen feedback is routine, it stops being an event. Your managers learn faster and no single conversation carries the weight of a performance review. Aim to make feedback so normal it's boring."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Accountability without micromanagement",
            "text": "Holding a manager accountable means being clear on the **outcome and the deadline**, then inspecting the result — not hovering over the method. **Accountability vs. micromanagement** is the line between 'own the renewal forecast and I'll review it Thursday' and 'send me every email first.' You can be demanding on the what while staying hands-off on the how.\n\nOne caution across your US, Manila, and China teams: **cross-cultural feedback** norms differ. Direct public correction that reads as normal in one context can cause loss of face in another. Adjust the delivery — often private, often softer framing — while keeping the substance and the standard identical."
          }
        ],
