        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Bring a recommendation, not a menu",
            "text": "Authority shows in **recommendation framing**: instead of laying out options and asking 'what do you think?', you present the options and then state what you'd do and why. 'Here are three paths; I recommend the second because it protects the renewal at the lowest cost.' Executives can still override you, but you've done the thinking.\n\nThis is **owning the call**. Bringing only questions upward signals you want the executive to do your job; bringing a reasoned recommendation signals leadership. Even when you're genuinely unsure, take a position and label your confidence — a stance you can revise beats a blank you ask them to fill."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Delivering bad news without losing trust",
            "text": "**Delivering bad news** well means being early, direct, and paired with a plan. Executives forgive problems; they don't forgive surprises, especially late ones. Lead with the bad news plainly — no burying it mid-paragraph — then immediately state what you're doing about it and what you need.\n\nNever soften to the point of distortion. If a large brokerage is likely to churn, say 'likely to churn', not 'showing some engagement headwinds'. Precision under bad news is itself a trust signal: it tells the executive they'll always hear the real number from you first."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Managing up means adapting to them",
            "text": "**Managing up** is tailoring how you communicate to your executive's preferences — some want a one-line Slack, others a structured doc; some want daily pulse, others weekly depth. It's not flattery; it's reducing friction so your message actually gets absorbed.\n\nLearn their rhythm and their hot buttons. If your VP cares most about NRR and cash, lead your updates there even when other things feel urgent to you. Matching their frame doesn't mean hiding your view — it means packaging it so it's heard on the first pass."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Calibrate your confidence out loud",
            "text": "**Confidence calibration** is stating how sure you are, not just what you think. 'I'm highly confident the renewal closes' and 'I'd put this at a coin flip' guide an executive's own risk-taking very differently. Overclaiming burns trust when you're wrong; underclaiming makes you look indecisive.\n\nThe goal is to be reliably calibrated so leaders can act on your stated confidence directly. When you say 80%, it should mean 80%. Over time, well-calibrated confidence is what lets an executive delegate real decisions to you without re-checking your work."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "Flagging a likely enterprise churn",
          "text": "A $1,500/mo enterprise brokerage is trending toward non-renewal. You practice **delivering bad news**: 'For awareness and one decision — I now think this account is likely to churn at renewal, roughly 65% risk.' That's **confidence calibration** — a real number, not vague 'headwinds'. You then use **recommendation framing**: 'Three options exist; I recommend a targeted value recap plus a service credit, because it addresses their onboarding complaint at the lowest cost.' You're **owning the call**. And because you know your VP fixates on cash and NRR, you **manage up** by leading with the revenue impact, not the support-ticket history."
        },
