        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Credibility has two halves",
            "text": "People grant influence to those they find **credible**, and credibility splits into two parts. **Competence** is whether you know what you're talking about — accurate data, sound judgment, reliable delivery. **Character** is whether you can be trusted to act in good faith — honesty, follow-through, and not throwing others under the bus.\n\nBoth are required. High competence with low character reads as a dangerous operator people route around. High character with low competence reads as pleasant but not worth acting on. Cross-functional partners quietly grade you on both every time you interact."
          },
          {
            "heading": "The trust account",
            "text": "Think of every working relationship as a **trust account** you can deposit into or withdraw from. Delivering what you promised, giving credit, and being straight in a hard moment are deposits. Missing commitments, surprising people, or spinning the truth are withdrawals — and withdrawals cost several times what a deposit earns.\n\nThe practical implication is that influence is built long before you need it. When you finally bring a big ask to Engineering or Sales, you are spending a balance you accumulated over months of small, reliable interactions."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Consistency is the multiplier",
            "text": "Trust is built less by grand gestures than by **consistency** — being the same reliable, straight-dealing person in the small moments no one is watching. A counterpart who has seen you keep twenty tiny commitments will extend you the benefit of the doubt on the twenty-first, larger one.\n\nInconsistency, even occasional, resets the meter. One unreliable quarter after a strong year does more damage than the strong year did good, because it teaches people they cannot predict you — and predictability is the whole point of trust."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Bank before you borrow",
            "text": "The biggest mistake in lateral influence is showing up only when you need something. That pattern trains counterparts to brace whenever your name appears in their inbox. Instead, invest in **relationship capital** proactively: share useful customer intel, flag a risk that helps them, celebrate their win publicly.\n\nWhen you have banked genuine goodwill, your eventual ask feels like a natural continuation of a two-way relationship rather than a cold demand. You are borrowing against a balance you already built."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "Earning the Product team's trust before renewal season",
          "text": "Renewal season is three months out and you know you'll need Product to prioritize two churn-driving fixes. Instead of waiting, you start making **deposits** now: you send the Product Manager a clean monthly summary of the top customer complaints from your Manila support queue, you publicly credit their last release in an executive update, and you flag an emerging issue with the AI texting feature before it blows up. By the time you bring your renewal-critical ask, you have real **relationship capital** in the account. The PM already sees you as a **credible** partner who makes their job easier, so your request is weighed as a trusted colleague's, not a stranger's demand."
        },
        "pauseAndThink": {
          "question": "Why does showing up to a counterpart only when you need something undermine your influence?",
          "answer": "It trains them to associate you with withdrawals from the trust account and to brace for demands. Without prior deposits of relationship capital, your ask reads as a cold, one-sided request rather than part of a reciprocal relationship."
        },
