        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Framing sets the outcome",
            "text": "**Framing** is choosing which angle of your request to lead with. The same fix can be framed as 'my team is drowning' (your problem) or 'this is costing us renewals in the MidMarket segment' (a shared business problem). The second frame invites partnership; the first invites sympathy at best.\n\nGood framing connects your ask to something the listener already cares about — a metric, a risk, a goal — so the request feels like advancing their agenda rather than absorbing yours. Frame around their outcome, not your inconvenience."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Data plus narrative",
            "text": "Data alone rarely moves people; a story alone rarely convinces them. **Data-plus-narrative** pairs the two: the numbers establish that the problem is real and sized, and the narrative makes it matter. 'Fourteen brokerages representing $180K in ARR are at risk' is the data; the story of one specific broker who nearly walked makes it land.\n\nLead with a crisp headline, support it with two or three hard numbers, and anchor it in a concrete customer example. That combination is far more persuasive to a busy counterpart than a spreadsheet or an anecdote by itself."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Make one specific ask",
            "text": "Vague requests die quietly. 'Can Engineering help with the AI calling issues sometime?' gives no one anything to act on. **The specific ask** names exactly what you want, from whom, by when: 'Can we get the call-logging bug scoped into next sprint, and can you name one engineer as point?'\n\nSpecificity respects the counterpart's time and makes a yes easy to give. It also makes the boundary of the request clear, so you're not perceived as asking for an open-ended commitment. Always leave the conversation with a defined next step, not a vague good feeling."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Handle objections without a fight",
            "text": "Objections are information, not attacks. **Objection handling** starts by acknowledging the concern genuinely — 'you're right that the sprint is full' — before problem-solving together. Arguing or steamrolling a concern spends trust you worked hard to build.\n\nOften the objection reveals a constraint you can help remove: if the blocker is capacity, offer to have your team handle triage and reproduction so Engineering only does the fix. Meeting an objection with a collaborative adjustment, rather than a rebuttal, is what turns a maybe into a yes."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "Pitching the call-logging fix to Engineering",
          "text": "You've mapped the stakeholders and banked trust; now you make the ask. You **frame** it as a renewal risk, not a support headache: 'We're seeing MidMarket renewal risk tied to the AI-calling log bug.' You bring **data-plus-narrative**: fourteen accounts, $180K ARR, plus the story of one broker who called it 'unusable' on a save call last week. You make **the specific ask**: 'Can we scope the fix into next sprint with one named engineer?' When the lead objects that the sprint is full, you don't argue — you **handle the objection** by offering your Manila team to own reproduction and test cases so Engineering only writes the fix. You close by confirming a **commitment**: the bug goes into planning Thursday, and you'll send the repro steps by Wednesday."
        },
