        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Situation, complication, resolution",
            "text": "The oldest reliable structure for a data story has three beats: **situation** (the shared, agreed reality), **complication** (what changed or went wrong), and **resolution** (what you recommend). This arc, adapted from Barbara Minto, works because it starts on common ground before introducing tension, so the audience is with you before you challenge them.\n\nStarting with the complication feels efficient but skips the shared context, and the room spends its energy questioning your premise instead of your recommendation. Establish the situation first, even briefly."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Answer first, then support",
            "text": "In exec settings, use the **pyramid principle**: state your answer or recommendation at the top, then support it with grouped arguments, then back each with data. This is the opposite of a mystery-novel build-up. Busy leaders want the conclusion up front so they can interrogate your reasoning, not wait for a reveal.\n\n**Answer-first structure** also protects you when the meeting gets cut short. If you have five minutes instead of twenty, the decision has already been stated, and the remaining time only deepens the support."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Group evidence so it holds together",
            "text": "Under your recommendation, your supporting points should be **MECE** — mutually exclusive and collectively exhaustive — so they do not overlap and do not leave obvious gaps. Three clean, non-overlapping reasons are more convincing than seven tangled ones.\n\nA useful test: if a skeptic could say \"but you left out X\" or \"points two and three are the same thing,\" your grouping is not yet MECE. Tightening the groups is what makes an argument feel airtight rather than assembled."
          },
          {
            "heading": "The narrative spine",
            "text": "Think of your deck as having a **narrative spine**: read only the slide headlines top to bottom, and they should form a coherent argument on their own. If the headlines read as a logical paragraph, the deck has a spine; if they read as disconnected labels, it does not.\n\nThis is a fast diagnostic you can run on any deck in minutes. Fixing the spine usually means rewriting headlines and reordering, not rebuilding charts."
          }
        ],
