          {
            "heading": "Two kinds of leaving",
            "text": "Churn splits into two roots. **Voluntary churn** is a customer who decides to cancel — the agent who feels the leads aren't converting and stops paying. **Involuntary churn** is a customer who never chose to leave but drops off anyway, usually because a card expired or a payment failed. The playbooks are completely different, so naming which one you're facing is step one.\n\nAt Lofty, both are live. A frustrated solo agent questioning lead ROI is voluntary risk; a brokerage whose card silently declined at renewal is involuntary. Lumping them into one 'churn' bucket hides that a big slice of loss is a billing-systems problem, not a value problem."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Logos versus dollars",
            "text": "**Logo churn** counts customers lost; **revenue churn** counts dollars lost. They diverge because your customers aren't the same size. Losing ten solo agents at $449/mo stings far less than losing one enterprise brokerage at $1,500/mo plus seats.\n\nAs a Director you steer by revenue churn, because that's what the business feels, while still watching logo churn as an early-warning texture — a wave of small-account cancellations can signal a product or onboarding problem before it reaches the big accounts."
          },
          {
            "heading": "GRR and NRR",
            "text": "**Gross revenue retention (GRR)** measures how much recurring revenue you keep from existing customers, ignoring any growth — it can never exceed 100%. **Net revenue retention (NRR)** adds expansion (upsells, added seats, upgrades) on top, so a healthy book can exceed 100% even while some customers leave.\n\nGRR tells you how leaky the bucket is; NRR tells you whether expansion is outrunning the leak. A retention program is judged first on lifting GRR — plugging leaks — because expansion built on a leaky base is fragile."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Why retention beats acquisition",
            "text": "Retention **compounds**. Keeping a customer one extra year multiplies their lifetime value and lowers the effective cost of the original sale, while a churned customer erases the acquisition spend that won them. For a premium subscription like Lofty, a few points of GRR improvement can outweigh a quarter of new-logo effort.\n\nThat's why retention is a growth strategy, not a cleanup function. Every point of churn you prevent flows straight to the recurring base that acquisition then builds on top of."
          }
