        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "A renewal is a re-decision, not a formality",
            "text": "A renewal is the moment a customer re-decides to keep paying for Lofty. Even when a contract technically **auto-renews**, treating that renewal as automatic is how you get blindsided by a cancellation. The **renewal motion** is the deliberate set of steps — value recap, risk check, forecast, and conversation — you run every cycle to earn that re-decision on purpose.\n\nFor your realtor customers, the re-decision is sharpened by economics: they are commission-based small-business owners who ask 'did this pay for itself?' before every renewal. A renewal you did not actively manage is a renewal you left to chance."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Run the timeline backward from the end date",
            "text": "The **renewal timeline** is planned backward from the contract end date, not forward from today. For a typical Lofty annual agreement you want the value recap and first renewal conversation to happen well before the term ends — commonly 60 to 90 days out — so there is room to resolve objections before the deadline forces a rushed yes-or-no.\n\nThe earlier you start, the more the renewal feels like a natural continuation and the less it feels like a high-pressure billing event that invites a realtor to shop competitors."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Ownership: who drives each stage",
            "text": "A clean renewal has clear **renewal ownership**. In your world the CSM (your MidMarket Client Success team or the Manila SMB CSM team) typically drives value and risk, while the **Sr. Billing Specialist** and Manila billing team handle the contract, invoicing, and payment mechanics. Ambiguity about who owns the renewal conversation is a top cause of renewals slipping.\n\nOwnership does not mean working alone. The best renewals are a handoff-free relay: the CSM surfaces risk early, billing prepares terms, and you step in only for escalations or strategic accounts."
          },
          {
            "heading": "GRR is the scoreboard",
            "text": "**Gross Revenue Retention (GRR)** measures how much recurring revenue you keep from existing customers, excluding any upsell — it can never exceed 100%. It is the purest scoreboard for the renewal motion because it isolates whether you are holding onto what you already have, before expansion flatters the picture.\n\nKeep GRR conceptually separate from expansion. A strong renewal motion protects GRR first; expansion (covered later) is the upside you layer on top once retention is solid."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "The renewal you almost missed",
          "text": "A MidMarket brokerage on an annual Lofty plan is 45 days from its end date and no one has spoken to them about renewing. Because your **renewal motion** never triggered a value recap, you do not know their AI-booked appointment volume dropped last quarter. You are now negotiating under a deadline with an unhappy customer. Running the **renewal timeline** backward — starting at 90 days — would have surfaced the risk while you still had time to fix adoption and protect **Gross Revenue Retention**."
        },
