        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Segment on Value and Potential",
            "text": "**Segmentation** is dividing your customer base into groups that should be served differently. The two most useful axes are **current value** (what an account pays today) and **potential value** (how much it could grow or the risk it carries). A solo agent and a 40-seat brokerage do not belong in the same motion.\n\nThe common mistake is segmenting on revenue alone. A small team on a growth trajectory — a rising brokerage adding agents — may deserve more attention than a larger but stagnant account. Blending **current and potential value** keeps you from over-serving accounts that will never grow and under-serving the ones that will."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Assign a Touch Model to Each Segment",
            "text": "Once segments exist, each gets a **touch model**: enterprise brokerages to high-touch with a named CSM, mid-market to a lighter proactive motion, and the solo-agent long tail to tech-touch. The point of segmentation is not the labels — it is that the labels drive a different, resourced motion.\n\nMake the assignment explicit and written down. When your MidMarket Client Success team and your Manila SMB CSMs each know exactly which segment they own and what that segment is promised, capacity stops leaking across boundaries."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Guard Against Segment Drift",
            "text": "**Segment drift** happens when accounts change — a solo agent scales into a small team, or a brokerage sheds agents — but their segment and touch model never update. The result is enterprise effort on a shrunken account or a fast-growing customer stuck in an automated tier with no human noticing.\n\nRe-segment on a regular cadence, ideally quarterly, using fresh usage and revenue data. Segmentation is a living system, not a one-time spreadsheet."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "The rising brokerage in the wrong tier",
          "text": "A customer that started as a two-agent team on your core plan has quietly grown to twelve agents and is running heavy AI-dialer volume. Because your segmentation was set a year ago on **current value**, they're still in the solo-agent tech-touch tier and no CSM has ever called them. That's **segment drift**: their **potential value** now clearly warrants a proactive motion. A quarterly re-segment using current seat count and usage would have caught it and promoted them before a competitor did."
        },
