        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Measure leading, not just lagging",
            "text": "Renewal rate is a **lagging** indicator — by the time it moves, the onboarding that caused it is long past. Manage onboarding with **leading metrics**: days-to-first-value, activation rate, milestone completion within the first 30 days. These move now and predict retention later.\n\nBeware measuring the wrong thing. **Onboarding completion** (the CSM ticked every step) is not the same as **activation** (the customer reached real value). A high completion rate with low activation means your process is busy but not working. Anchor your dashboard on value reached, not tasks finished."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Build a feedback loop",
            "text": "An onboarding program improves only if it learns. Build a **feedback loop**: instrument where customers stall, ask newly activated customers what nearly stopped them, and route recurring friction back into the playbook. Your Manila support and CSM teams sit on the richest signal about where new customers get stuck — capture it systematically instead of letting it evaporate in individual tickets.\n\n**Cohort analysis** sharpens the loop: compare the 30-day activation of this month's signups against last month's, and against customers who later churned versus renewed. The gap tells you which onboarding changes actually mattered."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Tie onboarding to renewal and expansion",
            "text": "Onboarding is not done when the customer activates — it is the opening move of the **onboarding-to-renewal link**. Customers who reach value fast and build a habit renew and become expansion candidates; those who stalled become the failed-payment and churn cases your billing team chases months later.\n\nMake this link visible in executive reporting. Showing that faster **time-to-value** correlates with higher renewal turns onboarding from a cost center into a retention investment leadership will fund. That is the argument that earns your program more resources."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "A dashboard that changes behavior",
          "text": "Your onboarding looks healthy — 95% **completion** — yet SMB renewals disappoint. You add **activation rate** and **days-to-first-value** to the dashboard and run a **cohort analysis**: activated customers renew far better than merely 'completed' ones. You feed the stall points your Manila teams report back into the **playbook**, watch activation climb, and bring the **onboarding-to-renewal** correlation to your executive review. Leadership funds another CSM for the SMB segment because you framed onboarding as a **retention investment**, not a cost."
        },
