        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "You don't decide it's fixed — the customer does",
            "text": "An escalation is not resolved when engineering merges a fix; it is resolved when the customer confirms their problem is gone in their world. **Resolution confirmation** means going back to the customer, verifying the dialer is dialing and the billing is corrected on their account, and getting their explicit acknowledgment. Closing a case internally while the customer still sees a symptom is how a resolved escalation reopens hotter than before.\n\nVerify against the customer's original complaint in their own words, not against your internal ticket. The gap between 'engineering says it's fixed' and 'the customer agrees it's fixed' is where trust is won or lost."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Make them whole, proportionally",
            "text": "For real harm, resolving the bug is table stakes; you also address the damage. **Making the customer whole** can mean a billing credit for the double-charge, a service credit for the lost outreach days, or simply a sincere, specific acknowledgment of what the outage cost them during peak season. The remedy should be **proportional** — matched to the actual harm — and offered before the customer has to demand it.\n\nDon't over-buy loyalty with reflexive giveaways, and don't under-repair real damage to a premium account. A well-judged, proportional gesture signals that you take the relationship seriously; an absent or token one confirms the customer's fear that they don't matter."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Close the loop, and turn the save into loyalty",
            "text": "A **formal closure** is an explicit conversation, not a silently closed ticket: recap what happened, what you did, what will prevent a recurrence, and confirm the customer considers it done. Then deliver a short **value recap** that re-anchors why they invested in Lofty in the first place. This is where the **service recovery paradox** lives — a well-handled escalation can leave a customer more loyal than if nothing had ever gone wrong, because they've now seen how you show up under pressure.\n\nDon't waste that. Feed a saved, re-engaged account back to the CSM so the momentum carries into renewal, and make sure the customer hears a clear, human 'here's how we made sure this won't happen to you again.'"
          }
        ],
