        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Open with acknowledge, align, assure",
            "text": "A reliable de-escalation opening runs **acknowledge-align-assure**: name what happened and how it landed (\"You budgeted for results and got silence — that's frustrating\"), align yourself with their goal (\"I want your lead spend working as hard as you do\"), then assure a next step (\"Here's what I'm going to do today\"). This order signals you are on their side before you problem-solve.\n\nSkipping straight to \"assure\" reads as dismissive. The **acknowledge** step is what tells a flooded customer they were heard."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Swap trigger phrases for softer equivalents",
            "text": "Certain **trigger phrases** predictably raise the temperature: \"Actually…\", \"As I said…\", \"You should have…\", \"That's our policy,\" and \"Calm down.\" They assign blame or condescend. Replace them with **ownership language** — \"Let me take a look,\" \"Here's what I can do,\" \"I understand why that's confusing.\"\n\nA small wording change carries a large emotional payload. \"Unfortunately we can't\" becomes \"What I can do is,\" which points the customer toward a path instead of a wall."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Specific commitments beat vague reassurance",
            "text": "Vague reassurance (\"We'll look into it soon\") erodes trust because it sounds like a brush-off. **Specific over vague commitments** — \"I'll have an answer for you by end of day Thursday and I'll email you either way\" — rebuilds credibility because it is checkable.\n\nPair this with **reflective listening**: briefly play back what you heard (\"So the dialer dropped calls during your open house push\") before committing. It proves comprehension and catches misunderstandings before they become new grievances."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "Rewriting a support reply",
          "text": "Your Manila team drafts: \"Per our policy, AI texting compliance is the user's responsibility. You should have reviewed the settings.\" You coach a rewrite using **acknowledge-align-assure** and **ownership language**: \"I can see how the texting limits caught you off guard — that's a stressful surprise mid-campaign. I want this working cleanly for your team. Here's what I can do: I'll audit your settings today and send you a corrected setup by 3pm.\" Same facts, no **trigger phrases**, and a **specific commitment** the customer can hold you to."
        },
