          {
            "heading": "When email is making it worse",
            "text": "Email strips out tone, invites re-reading, and lets each side draft ammunition. Watch for **email amplification** signals: the thread is growing, messages arrive minutes apart, the customer is CC'ing others, or the same point is restated in bigger words. These mean the channel itself is now part of the problem.\n\nEmail has low **tone bandwidth** — warmth and sincerity don't survive the medium. A live voice carries reassurance that no carefully worded paragraph can, which is why a spiraling thread usually needs a call."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Offering the call without sounding defensive",
            "text": "The **channel-switch offer** should frame the call as service, not evasion: \"This is important enough that I'd rather talk it through than trade emails — can I call you at 2pm?\" Avoid framing that implies they're too heated for writing. Give a specific time and a clear purpose so it reads as respect for their time.\n\nFor a Lofty enterprise account, a proactive call offer from a US lead also signals the account is being taken seriously, which itself lowers the temperature before you've said a word about the issue."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Running the call, then closing the loop",
            "text": "A de-escalation **call structure** runs: open with acknowledgment, let them vent without interrupting, reflect back the core issue, agree on next steps, and confirm the timeline. Resist solving in the first 60 seconds — the venting is doing necessary work.\n\nAlways follow with a **written recap after a call**: a short email listing what you heard, what you committed to, and by when. This converts a warm moment into an accountable record and prevents the issue from re-escalating in a new thread."
          }
