          {
            "heading": "An escalation is a break in the normal path, not just an unhappy customer",
            "text": "A support ticket becomes an **escalation** when it can no longer be resolved by the normal owner within the normal process — because it exceeds their authority, crosses a team boundary, breaches a time limit, or carries business risk (a churn threat, a public complaint, a billing dispute). Not every frustrated realtor is an escalation, and not every escalation comes from an angry customer; a stuck IDX website bug that blocks a brokerage's launch is an escalation even if the tone is polite.\n\nThe practical test is ownership: if the person holding the ticket cannot move it forward alone, it needs to **route** somewhere with more authority, expertise, or reach. Designing a process means deciding, in advance, what those routes are."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Ad-hoc escalation is a tax you pay every time",
            "text": "Without a designed process, escalations get handled by whoever happens to notice and whoever happens to be senior — a **hero-driven** model. It feels fine at low volume, but it hides the true cost: inconsistent outcomes, senior people pulled into work below their level, and no data on what's actually breaking.\n\nA **designed process** replaces 'who do I ping?' with a known path. The goal is not more bureaucracy; it is making the right next step obvious so your Manila support team and US leads spend judgment on the customer, not on figuring out where the ticket goes."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Four components hold any process together",
            "text": "Every workable escalation process has four parts: **tiers** (levels the issue can move through), **triggers** (the conditions that move it up a tier), **SLAs** (the time commitments at each level), and **handoffs** (how context transfers cleanly between owners). Miss any one and the process leaks — tiers without triggers means nothing escalates until it's a fire; SLAs without handoffs means the clock keeps running while context is lost.\n\nThe rest of this course builds these four in order. Right now the job is to hold them as a set, because they only work together."
          },
          {
            "heading": "The point is to catch problems early",
            "text": "A mature process is judged less by how fast it fights fires and more by how early it catches them. The **early-catch principle** says the cheapest escalation is the one intercepted while it's still small — a lead-ROI complaint answered in the first ticket, not after the customer has emailed your CEO.\n\nThis reframes the whole design. You are not just building an emergency ladder; you are building a net that surfaces risk before it becomes an executive escalation."
          }
