        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Tiers are levels of authority and reach, not levels of smartness",
            "text": "A **tier** is defined by what the owner at that level can do, not by how skilled they are. **Tier 1** is your front line — the Manila support team resolving the majority of tickets within known playbooks. **Tier 2** is the US global support lead plus specialists (billing, website), who hold more authority and can make judgment calls Tier 1 can't. **Tier 3** is cross-functional and executive reach — Product, Engineering, or you as director — pulled in for business-risk decisions.\n\nThe trap is treating higher tiers as 'the smart people.' They aren't; they're the people with different **authority and reach**. Framing it that way keeps Tier 1 owning resolution rather than reflexively passing hard-but-solvable tickets upward."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Two directions of escalation: functional and hierarchical",
            "text": "**Hierarchical escalation** moves a ticket up the authority chain — Tier 1 to Tier 2 to Tier 3 — usually for decisions, exceptions, or risk. **Functional escalation** moves it sideways to a different specialty — a billing dispute to the Sr. Billing Specialist, a data-feed bug to the website team — without necessarily going 'up.'\n\nMost real escalations need both: your Manila support team escalates functionally to billing and, if the dollar amount or churn risk is high, hierarchically to a US lead. Naming the two directions prevents the common mistake of shoving every hard ticket straight up the management ladder when it really just needed the right specialist."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Define each tier's ownership boundary explicitly",
            "text": "For every tier, write down three things: what it **owns** (resolves itself), what it **routes** (and to whom), and what **authority** it holds (refund limits, exception approvals, when it can commit engineering time). An **ownership boundary** that's written down is what lets Tier 1 act confidently and lets Tier 2 trust that what reaches them genuinely needed them.\n\nVague boundaries cause two failures at once: Tier 1 escalates too much because they're unsure, and occasionally too little because they overreach on something risky. Precision at the boundary is what makes the whole ladder efficient."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Guard against tier bloat and skip-levels",
            "text": "Two failure modes deserve a rule each. **Tier bloat** — adding more and more levels — feels thorough but adds handoffs, and every handoff loses context and time; most CS orgs need only three tiers. **Skip-level escalation**, where a customer or rep jumps straight to you or an executive, bypasses the people who'd resolve it faster and buries the process.\n\nYou can't prevent every skip-level (a brokerage owner will email you directly), but you can route it back onto the track: acknowledge, then place it at the correct tier with context, rather than personally hero-solving it and teaching everyone that skipping works."
          }
        ],
