        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Timing beats frequency",
            "text": "The instinct is to hammer a declined card repeatedly, but recovery depends on **timing**, not volume. Insufficient-funds declines often clear after a payday, so spacing retries across several days — rather than five times in one hour — catches funds when they arrive. A well-spaced **retry schedule** across roughly a week recovers a large share of soft declines with a handful of attempts.\n\nSpacing also protects you. Card networks watch merchants who retry the same declined card too aggressively, and excessive retries can raise processing costs or flag your account. Patient, spaced attempts recover more and cost less."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Smart retries and decline-code routing",
            "text": "**Smart retries** use signals — the decline code, the card network, historical success patterns — to pick the best next attempt time instead of using one fixed interval. This is **decline-code routing**: an insufficient-funds soft decline gets patient retries, while a hard decline is routed straight to customer outreach because no retry will help.\n\nThe point is to spend attempts where they pay off. Retrying a permanently dead card is pure waste; retrying a temporarily short account at the right hour is nearly free recovery. Routing by decline code is what separates a smart system from a dumb loop."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Account Updater for expired cards",
            "text": "A large share of failures are simply expired or reissued cards. **Account Updater** services (offered through the card networks via your payment processor) automatically fetch the customer's new card number and expiry when their bank issues a replacement — recovering the payment with zero customer effort. This is the highest-leverage, lowest-friction fix in dunning.\n\nFor Lofty's realtors, who are busy and mobile, silently updating an expired card beats any email. Confirm with your processor that Account Updater is enabled; it can quietly recover a meaningful slice of failures before a single dunning message goes out."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Knowing when to stop",
            "text": "Every retry system needs a **retry cap** — a defined maximum number of attempts and a window after which you stop retrying and escalate to a person. Retrying forever annoys banks, inflates fees, and delays the real fix. When the cap is hit, the account moves from automated retries into the dunning communication sequence.\n\nSet the cap deliberately with your billing team so the handoff from machine to human is crisp. The retry engine's job is to recover the easy wins silently; anything it can't recover should be handed to outreach quickly, not left spinning."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "Tuning the retry window",
          "text": "Your Sr. Billing Specialist notices the current setup retries a declined ~$449/mo charge four times in the first two hours, then gives up. You redesign it: a spaced **retry schedule** over about a week for soft declines, **decline-code routing** so hard declines skip retries entirely, and confirmation that **Account Updater** is on for expired cards. You also set a **retry cap** of a few attempts, after which the account enters the dunning email sequence. The change means paydays and reissued cards get caught automatically before anyone is ever emailed."
        },
