        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "The shape of a sequence",
            "text": "A **dunning sequence** is the ordered series of messages sent after retries fail, each nudging the customer to update payment. A good sequence escalates gently: an early, low-key heads-up ('we couldn't process your payment — here's a quick link to fix it'), a mid-sequence reminder, and a final notice that access is at risk. Each touch has a single job and a clear next step.\n\nThe sequence should span the grace period, not fire all at once. Compressing every message into two days reads as panic and annoys a customer who simply needs a moment to update a card. Spreading touches gives room to recover while keeping the issue visible."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Tone: helpful, not accusatory",
            "text": "**Message tone** decides whether a customer feels helped or hassled. Lofty's customers are commission-based small-business owners who escalate quickly when billing feels off, so the voice must be warm and solution-oriented: assume the failure was an accident, make fixing it effortless, and never imply they're delinquent. 'Your payment didn't go through — update it here in 30 seconds' lands far better than 'Your account is past due.'\n\nEvery message needs one clear **call to action**: a single button or link to update the card. Multiple asks, guilt, or dense billing jargon depress the response you're trying to drive."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Multi-channel and in-app touches",
            "text": "Email alone underperforms. **Multi-channel outreach** — email plus SMS plus **in-app dunning** (a banner or modal the user sees when they log into Lofty) — meets customers where they actually are. A realtor living in the mobile app may never open the billing email but will see an in-app banner the moment they check their leads.\n\nMatch channel to urgency: gentle email early, an in-app prompt throughout, and an SMS reserved for the final notice when access is genuinely at risk. Because Lofty already runs SMS and in-app messaging for lead outreach, these channels are available for billing too — just be deliberate not to overwhelm."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Cadence and stopping",
            "text": "**Cadence** is the rhythm and spacing of touches. Too sparse and the payment lapses unnoticed; too dense and you train customers to tune you out or escalate. A sequence of a few well-spaced touches across the grace window, with rising urgency, generally outperforms a barrage.\n\nCrucially, the sequence must stop the instant payment succeeds — nothing erodes trust faster than a 'your payment failed' text arriving after the customer already fixed it. Wire the sequence to cancel on success so a recovered customer never gets a stale dunning message."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "Rebuilding the failed-payment emails",
          "text": "Lofty's current dunning is a single stern 'past due' email. You redesign it into a **dunning sequence**: day 1 a friendly email with a one-click update **call to action**, an **in-app dunning** banner running throughout so agents see it when they open the dialer, a mid-window reminder, and a final SMS only as access nears suspension. You rewrite the **message tone** to assume an honest mistake, and you insist the whole **cadence** cancels the moment a retry or update succeeds — so a realtor who already fixed their card never gets a nagging text."
        },
