        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "The grace period trade-off",
            "text": "A **grace period** is the window after a payment fails during which the customer keeps full access while dunning runs. Its length is a trade-off: too short and you cut off customers who'd have paid, converting recoverable revenue into real churn and angry escalations; too long and you give away weeks of a premium product for free, inviting abuse. For a high-value realtor tool, a window measured in days — long enough to catch a payday and a card update — usually strikes the balance.\n\nThe grace period is the container the dunning sequence lives in. Set it deliberately, because every downstream decision about messaging and access hangs off its length."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Soft dunning vs. hard dunning",
            "text": "**Soft dunning** keeps the customer in full possession of the product while you remind them — banners and emails, no loss of function. **Hard dunning** applies real friction: limiting features, then suspending access. The art is sequencing soft before hard, so a customer who simply forgot isn't punished before they've had a fair chance to fix it.\n\nEscalate access consistently: full access with reminders, then a degraded experience, then **suspension**. Moving straight to a hard cutoff on day one turns a recoverable billing blip into a churned, resentful customer who tells other agents about it."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Suspension, not deletion",
            "text": "When the grace period ends unpaid, **suspension** freezes access but preserves the account. This is deliberate: Lofty holds a realtor's leads, contacts, transaction pipeline, and AI-nurtured relationships. Deleting that data the moment a card fails destroys the very thing that makes **reactivation** easy and would be catastrophic if the failure was involuntary.\n\nSound **data retention** keeps a suspended customer's data intact for a defined period so that paying reactivates them instantly, right where they left off. Frictionless reactivation is itself a recovery lever — the easier it is to come back, the more lapsed customers do."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Protecting goodwill",
            "text": "How you handle a lapse is remembered. A realtor who was suspended cleanly, kept their data, and reactivated in one click stays a customer; one who lost their pipeline and got a cold shutoff churns for good and warns their brokerage. Because Lofty's customers are cost-sensitive and quick to escalate, the grace-and-suspension policy is a customer-experience decision as much as a billing one.\n\nMake sure Support and CS know the policy so a lapsed customer who calls gets a consistent, humane answer. The goal is that even a suspended customer feels the door was left open, not slammed."
          }
        ],
