        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Retry with intelligence, not brute force",
            "text": "A **smart retry** schedules re-attempts based on why the charge failed rather than hammering the card on a fixed loop. Soft declines like insufficient funds are timed around when balance is likely to return — near month-end or a probable commission deposit — while hard declines aren't retried at all because the card can't approve. Blind daily retries burn issuer goodwill and can get a merchant flagged.\n\nGood retry logic also spaces attempts out over days, not hours, and caps the number of tries. The goal is to catch the moment the account can pay without training the bank to see you as abusive."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Dunning across channels",
            "text": "A **dunning sequence** is the series of messages that runs while a payment is unresolved: 'we couldn't process your payment; please update your card.' The strongest sequences use **multi-channel outreach** — email plus in-app banners, and for a platform like Lofty, potentially SMS — because a realtor living in their phone may never open a billing email but will tap an in-app alert.\n\nSpacing and tone matter. Early messages are gentle and helpful; later ones make the consequence clear without threatening. Every message needs a one-tap path to update the card, because friction at the update step quietly kills otherwise-willing recoveries."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Grace periods and win-back",
            "text": "A **grace period** keeps service alive for a set window after a payment fails, so a customer who simply had a bad balance day doesn't lose access to their CRM, leads, and pipeline overnight. Cutting a paying realtor off instantly over one soft decline is how you turn a recoverable failure into a real, angry cancellation.\n\nWhen retries and dunning still fail and the account lapses, **win-back** is the final stage: a later, lighter-touch attempt to re-engage the customer and restore billing, sometimes weeks out. Because these customers often left by accident, a well-timed win-back can recover accounts that everyone else had already written off as churned."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "A four-day save",
          "text": "A team-tier Lofty account fails on insufficient funds. Instead of retrying hourly, your **smart retry** waits and re-attempts near the realtor's typical commission-deposit timing. Meanwhile a **dunning sequence** fires across email and an in-app banner, each with a one-tap update-card link — **multi-channel outreach** because this agent lives in the app, not their inbox. A short **grace period** keeps their leads and pipeline live so they aren't cut off mid-deal. The retry clears on day four. Had you suspended instantly, you'd likely have converted a bad-balance day into a genuine cancellation."
        },
