        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "The chargeback lifecycle",
            "text": "A **chargeback** happens when a customer disputes a charge directly with their bank or card network instead of asking you for a refund. The **chargeback lifecycle** runs: the customer disputes, the card network provisionally pulls the funds back, you receive the notice, and you either accept the loss or fight it with evidence.\n\nChargebacks cost more than the disputed amount because networks add fees and track your **chargeback rate**; too many can jeopardize your ability to process cards at all. That makes them worse than a plain refund, which is why catching a would-be chargeback earlier and turning it into a support conversation is almost always cheaper."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Representment: fighting a chargeback",
            "text": "**Representment** is the process of contesting a chargeback by submitting evidence that the charge was legitimate: the signed contract, usage logs, terms the customer agreed to, and records of the service delivered. For a SaaS platform like Lofty, strong evidence is proof the account was active and features like AI calling were used during the disputed period.\n\nYou don't win representment by arguing; you win by documentation. The teams that recover the most disputed revenue are the ones that can quickly assemble a clean evidence package, which means the groundwork — clear terms, logged usage, saved receipts — has to exist long before the dispute arrives."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Friendly fraud versus real disputes",
            "text": "**Friendly fraud** is when a customer disputes a charge they actually authorized — often because they forgot the subscription, didn't recognize the descriptor on their statement, or found it easier than requesting a refund. It looks like fraud to the bank but the purchase was legitimate, and it's a large share of SaaS chargebacks.\n\nDistinguish this from a genuine dispute (you really did bill wrong) and true fraud (a stolen card). Each needs a different response: fix your error for genuine disputes, present evidence for friendly fraud, and accept and secure the account for true fraud. Misreading the category wastes effort and can antagonize a customer who had a legitimate complaint."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Prevention beats representment",
            "text": "The cheapest chargeback is the one that never happens. **Chargeback prevention** includes a clear, recognizable billing descriptor on statements, proactive renewal reminders, an easy in-product way to get a refund or cancel, and responsive support so a frustrated customer calls you before they call their bank. Every one of these diverts a would-be dispute into a cheaper path.\n\nYour **dispute rate** — disputes as a share of transactions — is the metric to watch. A rising rate usually points to a systemic cause: an unclear descriptor, a confusing renewal, or a support queue so slow that customers give up and dispute instead. Fixing the cause beats winning individual cases."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "The forgotten annual renewal chargeback",
          "text": "A solo agent who paused active selling forgets their Lofty subscription auto-renewed annually, doesn't recognize the statement descriptor, and files a **chargeback** instead of contacting support. This is classic **friendly fraud**: the charge was authorized, but it looks like fraud to the bank. Your billing team wins the **representment** by submitting the signed agreement and login and AI-texting usage logs — but you note that winning cost fees and effort. The better fix is **prevention**: you push for a clearer billing descriptor and a pre-renewal email, because your **dispute rate** for annual plans has been creeping up and the pattern is systemic, not a one-off."
        },
