        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Refund, credit, or adjustment",
            "text": "These are three different tools. A **refund** returns cash to the customer's card and permanently leaves your revenue. A **service credit** applies value toward future Lofty charges, keeping the money in the relationship and giving the customer a reason to stay another cycle. A **goodwill adjustment** is a smaller concession — waiving a fee or crediting a partial amount — to resolve a complaint without a full refund.\n\nDefaulting to cash refunds when a **service credit** would satisfy the customer is a common way billing teams leak revenue. The skill is matching the tool to the situation: refund a genuine billing error, but offer a credit when the goal is to smooth a relationship you want to keep."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Refund policy that protects trust and margin",
            "text": "A good **refund policy** is written down, applied consistently, and gives frontline agents clear authority up to a threshold so customers get fast answers. Inconsistency is the real enemy: if one agent refunds freely and another refuses, customers learn to escalate and argue, which trains bad behavior and burns your team's time.\n\nThe policy should distinguish clear-cut cases (you billed in error — refund promptly) from discretionary ones (the customer is unhappy but was billed correctly — use judgment and credits). Publishing the thresholds internally lets your Manila billing team resolve most cases without escalating to your Sr. Billing Specialist or to you."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Credits as a retention tool",
            "text": "A **service credit** is not just a cheaper refund; it can be a retention move. Applying a credit toward the next month keeps the customer active, buys time for your CSM to re-establish value, and often costs less in margin than the lifetime value you'd lose to churn. Framed well, a credit says we're making this right and we want you to stay.\n\nBe deliberate, though. Credits handed out reflexively become an expectation and a source of **margin leakage**. Tie them to a specific reason and, where possible, to a forward commitment — a renewal, an onboarding restart, or an expansion conversation — so the concession buys something back."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Watching for margin leakage",
            "text": "**Margin leakage** is the slow bleed of small refunds, credits, and waived fees that individually look trivial but collectively erode profitability. Because each concession is easy to justify in the moment, no single one triggers scrutiny, which is exactly why it needs to be measured in aggregate.\n\nTrack total credits and refunds by reason and by team member. If one segment or one agent accounts for an outsized share, you've found either a product problem generating complaints or an inconsistent policy being applied. Either way, aggregate visibility is what converts a hidden leak into a fixable process."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "The onboarding-gone-wrong concession",
          "text": "An SMB customer had a rough onboarding, threatens to cancel, and demands a full month's **refund**. A reflexive cash refund would leave the relationship on shaky ground and permanently exit that revenue. Instead you coach your billing lead and the SMB CSM to offer a **service credit** toward next month paired with a re-onboarding session — turning the concession into a **retention** move that keeps the customer active while your team rebuilds value. You also note this is the third onboarding-related concession this month and ask for a **margin leakage** breakdown by reason, suspecting an onboarding process gap rather than isolated bad luck."
        },
