        "key": "trustworthy-analysis",
        "title": "From Query to Trustworthy Answer",
        "focus": "Caps the course by turning correct syntax into correct conclusions: sanity checks, dates, and knowing the limits of a self-serve number.",
        "objectives": [
          "Apply sanity checks before trusting a query result",
          "Handle date ranges correctly to avoid off-by-one errors",
          "Decide when a self-serve query is enough and when to escalate to the data team"
        ],
        "concepts": [
          "Sanity checking",
          "Date range filtering",
          "Sorting and limiting",
          "Definitional alignment",
          "Knowing your limits"
        ],
        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Sanity-check before you believe your own query",
            "text": "A query always returns something; that doesn't make it right. **Sanity checking** means testing a result against what you already know before you act on it. Does the total customer count roughly match what you expect? Does revenue by tier sum to the company total? Spot-check one account by hand. A number that's off by 10x usually means a fan-out, a missing filter, or a NULL problem, not a surprising truth about the business.\n\nThe discipline is simple: never present a figure you haven't cross-checked at least once. A wrong number delivered confidently to the board is worse than no number."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Dates are where quiet errors hide",
            "text": "**Date range filtering** trips up almost everyone. To get last quarter you might write `WHERE created_date >= '2026-04-01' AND created_date < '2026-07-01'`. Using `<` on the day after the period, rather than `<=` on the last day, avoids missing or including a partial final day. Also confirm whether timestamps are in UTC or local time, because a day boundary can shift results.\n\nUse **sorting and limiting** to make results readable: `ORDER BY mrr DESC LIMIT 10` gives you the top ten accounts by revenue. Sorting doesn't change the numbers, but it puts the rows that matter on top."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Agree on the definition, and know your limits",
            "text": "The hardest part of an answer isn't the SQL, it's **definitional alignment**: does 'active customer' mean logged in this month, or billing this month, or not cancelled? Two correct queries with different definitions produce different numbers and a pointless argument. Write the definition down and confirm it before quoting the figure.\n\nFinally, practice **knowing your limits**. Self-serve SQL is perfect for quick, single-source questions and gut-checks. But for board-reported revenue, blended multi-system metrics, or anything with legal or financial weight, route it through your data team so the definitions and pipelines are validated. Knowing which bucket a question falls into is itself a leadership skill."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "The churn number you almost reported",
          "text": "Before a QBR you query churned enterprise accounts for last quarter and get 47. You pause for a **sanity check**: that feels high, so you spot-check five of them and find three merely downgraded, not churned, a **definitional alignment** gap on what 'churned' means. You also notice your **date range** used `<= '2026-06-30'` against UTC timestamps, pulling in a sliver of accounts that actually cancelled in July. You fix the definition and the boundary, re-run, and get a defensible 31. Because this feeds board-level revenue, you also send it to your **data team** to confirm before it goes in the deck. That single pause is the difference between leading with a real number and walking back a wrong one in front of executives."
        },
        "pauseAndThink": {
          "question": "Two analysts report different 'active customer' counts from the same database and both queries are technically correct. What is the most likely cause, and how do you resolve it?",
          "answer": "They're almost certainly using different definitions of 'active' (logged in vs. billing vs. not cancelled). Resolve it by writing down and agreeing on the definition first, then re-running against that shared definition, this is definitional alignment, not a SQL bug."
        },
        "glossary": [
          {
            "term": "Sanity checking",
            "definition": "Testing a query result against what you already know before acting on it."
          },
          {
            "term": "Date range filtering",
            "definition": "Restricting rows to a time period, carefully handling day boundaries and time zones."
          },
          {
            "term": "ORDER BY / LIMIT",
            "definition": "Clauses that sort rows and cap how many are returned, so the important rows surface first."
          },
          {
            "term": "Definitional alignment",
            "definition": "Agreeing on exactly what a metric like 'active customer' means before quoting it."
          },
          {
            "term": "Knowing your limits",
            "definition": "Recognizing when a question needs the validated pipelines of the data team rather than a quick self-serve query."
          }
        ],
        "insights": [
          "A query always returns something, so **sanity checking** against what you already know is what separates a real answer from a confident wrong one.",
          "**Date range filtering** and time zones are where quiet off-by-one errors hide, so handle day boundaries with < on the day after, not <= on the last day.",
          "Most metric disputes are **definitional alignment** problems, not SQL bugs, and knowing when to route a question to the **data team** is itself a leadership skill."
        ],
        "action": "Take one number you've quoted recently, re-derive it yourself, and **sanity-check** it by spot-checking a handful of rows and confirming the **definition** everyone assumed.",
        "leadershipTakeaway": "The credibility of a data-driven leader rests less on writing clever SQL and more on the discipline of cross-checking, aligning definitions, and knowing which questions to escalate.",
        "productivityTip": "Keep a shared glossary of your team's key metric definitions so 'active,' 'churned,' and 'at-risk' mean one thing across every report.",
        "discussionQ": "Which of your team's headline metrics lacks a written, agreed definition, and what confusion has that already caused?",
