        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Time-to-value anchors onboarding",
            "text": "**Time-to-value** (TTV) is how long it takes a new customer to reach their first meaningful outcome — for a realtor, perhaps the first booked appointment from autonomous lead engagement. Shorter TTV correlates strongly with adoption and retention, because customers who feel value early stick.\n\nTTV makes onboarding measurable. If your onboarding drags and the customer has paid premium prices without a win, the risk of early churn climbs well before the first renewal."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Adoption rate over time",
            "text": "**Product adoption rate** measures the share of a customer's paid capabilities they actively use — for example, whether a brokerage that bought AI calling, IDX websites, and marketing automation actually runs all three. Rising adoption is a leading signal of expansion potential; flat adoption of paid features signals wasted spend and churn risk.\n\nTrack adoption at the feature level, not just overall login activity. A customer can log in daily and still ignore the very feature that justifies their tier."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Coverage ratios and capacity",
            "text": "A **coverage ratio** expresses how much book or how many accounts each CSM carries — often accounts per CSM or revenue under management per CSM. It drives staffing: too high and CSMs cannot be proactive; too low and the model is uneconomic. Segments should carry different ratios, with high-touch MidMarket lighter than pooled SMB.\n\nCoverage ratios are how you argue for headcount with evidence. When your Manila SMB CSM team is stretched thin, the ratio against a healthy benchmark is the number an executive will act on."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Support metrics without the gaming",
            "text": "**First response time** and **resolution time** measure how quickly support acknowledges and closes issues. They matter for your Manila support team, but they are easy to distort. Optimizing purely for speed invites **metric gaming**: agents close tickets prematurely to hit resolution targets, and reopened tickets or falling CES reveal the damage.\n\nPair every speed metric with a quality metric — CES, CSAT, or reopen rate — so no one wins by hitting a time target at the customer's expense. A metric that can be gamed will be gamed if it is the only thing rewarded."
          }
        ],
