        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Urgency is not importance",
            "text": "The **Eisenhower matrix** sorts work on two axes: urgent versus not-urgent, and important versus not-important. Urgency is about deadlines and noise; **importance** is about impact on your real goals. The trap is that urgent-but-unimportant work — a same-hour report request, a Slack ping — masquerades as priority because it is loud, while important-but-not-yet-urgent work like fixing a churn driver quietly waits.\n\nThe matrix's payoff is the two hard quadrants. Urgent-and-important work you do now. Important-but-not-urgent work you must schedule and protect, because it is where leverage lives. Urgent-but-unimportant work you delegate, and not-urgent-not-important work you delete without guilt."
          },
          {
            "heading": "The impact versus effort screen",
            "text": "When you have a list of possible initiatives, plot each on **impact** (how much it moves an outcome) against **effort** (what it costs to do). High-impact, low-effort items are quick wins you should grab immediately. High-impact, high-effort items are major bets you plan deliberately. Low-impact, low-effort items are fill-in work, and low-impact, high-effort items are traps to avoid.\n\nThis screen is fast and defensible because it forces you to state impact and cost explicitly rather than defaulting to whatever arrived most recently. For a director juggling support, billing, and website work, it lets you compare apples across teams on one shared grid."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Weighted scoring beats gut feel",
            "text": "When items are close, **weighted scoring** removes bias: list a few criteria that matter — say revenue impact, customer risk, and effort — assign each a weight, score every item against each criterion, and total them. The item with the highest weighted total wins, regardless of who championed it.\n\nThe hidden benefit is not just the number; it is that the criteria are visible and agreed in advance. That neutralizes the **loudest-voice bias**, the natural pull to prioritize whichever stakeholder escalated hardest. When a VP asks why their request slipped, you can point to shared criteria rather than defend a gut call."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Match the tool to the decision",
            "text": "These tools are not interchangeable. The Eisenhower matrix is best for sorting your own daily and weekly inflow. The impact/effort screen shines when comparing a set of initiatives. Weighted scoring is worth the overhead only for high-stakes, contested decisions where you need a transparent, defensible ranking.\n\nOverusing a heavy framework on trivial choices is itself a prioritization failure. The point of a framework is to make a good decision faster and more consistently — if it slows you down on a low-stakes call, you have picked the wrong tool for the job."
          }
        ],
