        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "A meeting is your most expensive tool",
            "text": "The true cost of a meeting is not one hour on your calendar — it is one hour multiplied by every attendee, plus the fragmentation of their day around it. A 60-minute status call with eight people is a full working day consumed. When you lead across your Manila support team, your website PM, and billing, you are spending payroll every time you hit send on an invite.\n\nBecause the cost is hidden and shared, meetings multiply until someone applies **discipline**. Treating meeting time as a scarce budget — not a free default — is the first habit of a leader who respects both outcomes and people's focus."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Every meeting needs one purpose",
            "text": "A meeting without a stated purpose becomes a meeting about everything, which means it decides nothing. Before you schedule, finish the sentence: \"By the end, we will have ______.\" That blank is a **decision made**, a **problem solved**, alignment reached, or relationships built — not \"discussed the project.\"\n\nIf you cannot fill the blank, you do not have a meeting; you have a status update that belongs in writing. The **purpose statement** is the single most powerful filter you have, because it exposes empty meetings before they eat anyone's day."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Sync when it's ambiguous, async when it's not",
            "text": "Live meetings are worth their cost for work that is high in ambiguity, emotion, or back-and-forth: debating a churn-save strategy, giving difficult feedback, or building trust with a team you rarely see. Information that flows one direction — status, FYIs, metrics — should default to **async** written form, where people consume it on their own schedule.\n\nThe test is simple: if a topic mostly needs people to know something, write it. If it needs people to think together in real time, meet. Choosing wrong in either direction is the root of both wasted meetings and slow, chaotic email threads."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "The recurring status call you inherited",
          "text": "You inherit a standing weekly call between your US website PM and the Manila website team. Thirty minutes, six people, mostly each person reciting what they did. Apply the **purpose test**: fill in \"by the end we will have ______.\" You cannot — it is pure status, flowing one direction. You convert it to an **async** written update in your shared doc and keep only a shorter biweekly live slot reserved for actual blockers and decisions. You just returned roughly five person-hours a week to the team without losing any real coordination."
        },
