        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "The standup surfaces blockers, not status",
            "text": "A **daily standup** is a short (15-minute) sync where the team aligns on progress toward the goal and, above all, surfaces **blockers** — anything stopping work from moving. The classic frame is what moved, what's next, and what's in my way, but the real payload is that last part.\n\nStandups fail when they become a status report to the manager. The fix is to make it a peer coordination event: people talk to each other, blockers get owned on the spot, and detailed problem-solving is taken offline to a smaller group afterward rather than held hostage by the whole team's time."
          },
          {
            "heading": "The review inspects real outcomes",
            "text": "At the end of a sprint, the **sprint review** is where the team shows the actual working outcome to the people who care — stakeholders, and ideally a proxy for the customer. It's a demo of done work, not a slide about planned work, which keeps everyone honest about what 'done' means.\n\nFor your world, a review might mean walking your leadership or a partnering team through the rebuilt onboarding flow live, or showing the real recovery-rate numbers a billing sprint produced. The review closes the loop between what was committed and what was delivered, and it's where you gather feedback that reshapes the next backlog."
          },
          {
            "heading": "The retrospective improves the process itself",
            "text": "The **retrospective** is the team's private look not at the work but at how they worked — what went well, what didn't, and what one or two things to change next iteration. It is the dedicated engine of **continuous improvement**, and it's the ceremony teams most often skip and most need.\n\nA good retro is blameless: you examine the system and the process, not who to fault, so people speak honestly. And it must produce a small number of concrete, owned actions — a retro that only vents produces nothing. One improvement actually implemented beats ten insights that evaporate."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Ceremonies are feedback loops at different tempos",
            "text": "See the ceremonies as **feedback loops** running at different speeds: the standup is a daily loop for coordination, the review is a per-sprint loop for validating outcomes, and the retro is a per-sprint loop for improving the process. Each inspects something and adapts.\n\nThe discipline is to keep each loop doing its own job. When a standup drifts into deep problem-solving or a review turns into a retro, both jobs get done poorly. Right-size each ceremony, and drop any that has stopped producing value rather than running it out of habit — that habit is exactly the cargo-cult trap."
          }
        ],
