        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "An Objective is a qualitative destination",
            "text": "An **Objective** answers 'where do we want to go?' It is a short, memorable, qualitative statement of intent that should feel meaningful and slightly uncomfortable to your team. Good objectives inspire without being vague to the point of meaning nothing: 'Make onboarding the reason brokerages stay' beats 'Improve onboarding.'\n\nAn objective is deliberately not a number. It sets direction and motivation. The measurement comes from its key results, which is why an objective without key results is just a slogan."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Key Results are the measurable proof",
            "text": "A **Key Result** answers 'how will we know we got there?' Each objective carries two to five key results, and every one must be numeric and verifiable — a metric with a starting value and a target. If you can argue at quarter-end about whether it was met, it was written wrong.\n\nThe critical discipline is that key results measure **outcomes**, not activity. 'Launch three new help articles' is an output you fully control; 'cut onboarding-related support tickets from 40 to 25 per week' is an outcome that proves the articles worked. OKRs reward the result, not the effort."
          },
          {
            "heading": "OKRs are not KPIs and not a task list",
            "text": "A **KPI** is a health metric you monitor continuously — CSAT, first-response time, monthly churn. An OKR is a focused, time-boxed push to change something. A KPI can become the key result of an OKR when you decide to move it, but most KPIs just run in the background. Confusing the two turns your OKRs into a dashboard of everything, which is the same as focusing on nothing.\n\nSimilarly, OKRs are not your task list. Tasks are the work you'll do; key results are the change that work should produce. Keep them separate or you'll grade yourself on being busy."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Aspirational versus committed",
            "text": "Two flavors exist. **Committed OKRs** are promises you expect to fully hit — a renewal target you'll be held to. **Aspirational (stretch) OKRs** are ambitious bets where landing around 70 percent is a genuine success and hitting 100 percent means you aimed too low. Labeling which is which prevents your Manila and US teams from either sandbagging safe targets or burning out chasing an impossible one they thought was a hard commitment."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "Rewriting a fuzzy team goal",
          "text": "Your US global support lead proposes the goal 'provide great support this quarter.' That is an **Objective** at best, and a weak one. You keep the intent but sharpen it to 'Make support fast enough that customers stop escalating,' then attach **Key Results**: reduce median first-response time from 6 hours to 2, cut executive escalations from 12 per month to 5, and lift support CSAT from 4.1 to 4.4. Notice you resisted writing 'hire two agents' or 'publish a macro library' as key results — those are the tasks your team will run, while the key results are the **outcomes** those tasks must produce."
        },
