        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "The failure modes are predictable",
            "text": "Most OKR programs fail the same handful of ways: **too many OKRs** so nothing is truly a priority; using OKRs **as a task tracker** so the list becomes a to-do dump; **set-and-forget**, where goals are written once and never revisited; and linking scores to pay so honesty evaporates. None of these are exotic — they're the default gravity every rollout drifts toward.\n\nKnowing the failure modes by name lets you spot them early. When your OKR doc has fifteen objectives and reads like a sprint board, you don't have OKRs — you have a backlog with ambitions."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Focus is the whole point",
            "text": "The discipline OKRs enforce is **focus** — a team should carry only two or three objectives with a few key results each. The value isn't the goals you write down; it's the goals you consciously leave off. Saying no to a worthy-but-not-now goal is the hardest and most important move, and as director you model it or nobody else will.\n\nA short OKR list also survives contact with a reactive, people-heavy quarter. Overload guarantees that when escalations hit, the OKRs are the first thing abandoned."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Roll out in phases, not all at once",
            "text": "Don't OKR your entire org on day one. A **phased rollout** starts with one or two teams for a quarter, learns what confuses people, and builds a couple of examples others can copy. Set expectations that the first cycle will be rough — early OKRs are usually too many, too task-like, and mis-scored, and that's normal.\n\nRun a real retrospective after cycle one and fix the process before widening. A believable, imperfect rollout that improves each quarter beats a grand launch that collapses under its own paperwork."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Adapt the framework to your teams",
            "text": "OKRs are a tool, not a religion. A billing/collections team with steady operational metrics may need mostly guardrail-style key results, while a CS team chasing retention needs aspirational ones. Your cross-cultural org matters too: teams unused to public stretch goals may first read a 0.7 as failure, so you explain the scoring philosophy before the first cycle rather than after a demoralizing grade.\n\nThe goal is better decisions and clearer focus, not framework purity. If a rule isn't serving those, bend it deliberately and say why."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "Your first OKR quarter across the org",
          "text": "You decide against OKR-ing every team at once. Your **phased rollout** starts with just the US MidMarket Client Success and Manila onboarding teams, each capped at two objectives to enforce **focus**. You brief both on the **0.7** scoring philosophy up front, since the Manila team might otherwise read a stretch score as failure. Mid-quarter you catch the classic drift — the onboarding doc has swollen into a fifteen-item **task tracker** — and you cut it back to three real key results. At quarter-end you run a retrospective, fix the two biggest process problems, and only then extend OKRs to billing and support. You've traded a grand launch for a rollout that actually survives its first collision with a wave of escalations."
        },
