        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "No target is meaningful without a baseline",
            "text": "A **baseline** is the current, honest level of a KPI before you try to change it, measured over enough time to smooth out noise. Setting a target before you know your baseline is guessing — 'get first-response time to two hours' means nothing until you know whether you are at three hours or ten. Always spend the first weeks of a new KPI just measuring, resisting the urge to attach a goal before the data has a shape.",
            "text2": "A baseline also protects you politically. When you later claim improvement, a documented starting point is the difference between a credible result and a number your executives suspect you moved by changing the definition."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Benchmarks tell you what 'good' looks like elsewhere",
            "text": "A **benchmark** is a reference level from outside your immediate team — an industry norm, a best-in-class figure, or another segment inside Lofty. Benchmarks stop you from celebrating a target that is mediocre by market standards or from setting one that is impossibly above what anyone achieves. Use them as context, not gospel: a benchmark from a different customer mix or business model can mislead, so weight internal comparisons and be honest about whether a public figure is truly comparable."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Choose a targeting method that fits the KPI's maturity",
            "text": "**Target setting** generally follows one of three logics. Internal-trend targets extrapolate your own trajectory ('improve 10% on last quarter') and suit new or volatile KPIs. Benchmark targets aim at an external standard and suit mature areas where good is well understood. Stretch targets deliberately set an ambitious level to force new thinking. The art is matching the method to the situation: stretch goals on a KPI you barely measure yet will just breed cynicism.",
            "text2": "Whichever you pick, write down the assumption behind the number. A target with no stated rationale invites endless renegotiation, while 'we chose 8% because best-in-class is 6% and we are at 12%' ends the debate."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Thresholds turn a target into a trigger",
            "text": "A single target line is less useful than **thresholds and bands** — the green, amber, and red zones that tell people when to relax, watch, and act. Bands acknowledge that KPIs are noisy: a metric one point off target is not the same emergency as one that has crossed into the red. Define the action attached to each band in advance, so amber means 'CSM lead reviews the account list this week' rather than a vague sense of worry."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Balance stretch against realism to protect credibility",
            "text": "**Stretch vs. realistic** is a genuine tension. Targets set too low get hit and teach nothing; targets set impossibly high get missed, ignored, and eventually gamed. A useful rule is that a target should be reachable in roughly seven or eight tries out of ten with real effort — hard enough to require change, achievable enough that the team believes it. When you must set a true stretch goal, label it as such and separate it from the committed target so a miss does not read as failure."
          }
        ],
