        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "IDX is permission to display, not the database itself",
            "text": "**IDX** stands for Internet Data Exchange. It is the framework of rules and data access that lets a broker display other members' MLS listings on their own public website. The MLS is the source; **IDX** is the specific program that authorizes and governs pulling those listings out to show consumers.\n\nThis distinction matters for support. When a customer says 'my IDX is broken,' they almost never mean the MLS database is down — they mean the pipeline that feeds listings into their website has a problem. Lofty's IDX agent websites are essentially a licensed display of that shared inventory."
          },
          {
            "heading": "The journey of a listing to a Lofty site",
            "text": "A listing is entered into the MLS by the listing agent, then made available through an **IDX feed** — a governed data connection the MLS provides to authorized recipients. Lofty ingests that feed, maps the data into its website product, and displays it to the agent's site visitors.\n\nBecause the feed is a copy that syncs on a schedule, the website is only ever as current as the last sync. A price change entered in the MLS at 9am may not appear on the agent's Lofty site until the next **feed refresh cadence** completes — a common source of 'the price is wrong' tickets that are actually just timing."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Opt-in, opt-out, and attribution",
            "text": "Not every listing is guaranteed to appear on every IDX site. Sellers and listing brokers can, under many MLS rules, use **opt-in and opt-out** to exclude a listing from IDX display. When a customer complains a specific home is missing, an opt-out is a real possible cause, not a bug.\n\nEvery IDX-displayed listing must also carry **listing broker attribution** — the name of the brokerage that actually holds the listing — so consumers aren't misled into thinking the displaying agent listed it. This attribution requirement is non-negotiable and shapes how listing detail pages are designed."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "The '9am price change isn't showing' ticket",
          "text": "An agent on a ~$449/mo Lofty plan calls your power dialer team furious that a listing on their site still shows the old price hours after they updated it. Before anyone escalates to engineering, the likely answer is the **feed refresh cadence**: the **IDX feed** syncs on a schedule, so the site reflects the MLS as of the last sync, not the instant. Separately, if a whole listing is missing rather than stale, suspect an **opt-out** by the seller, not a Lofty defect. Teaching support to check 'stale = timing, missing = opt-out or attribution' before escalating protects your engineering partners from noise."
        },
