        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "RESO exists to make fragmented data speak one language",
            "text": "Because there are hundreds of MLSs, there were historically hundreds of ways to describe the same thing — one MLS's 'Baths' is another's 'BathroomsTotal.' **RESO**, the Real Estate Standards Organization, publishes standards so that data from different MLSs can be understood consistently by software.\n\nRESO is the reason a vendor like Lofty can build one product that ingests many feeds instead of writing bespoke code for every single MLS. Where RESO compliance is strong, integration is cheaper and faster; where it's weak or partial, engineering has to paper over the gaps."
          },
          {
            "heading": "The Data Dictionary and the Web API",
            "text": "Two RESO standards matter most. The **RESO Data Dictionary** defines a common set of field names and values — so 'PropertyType' means the same thing everywhere it's followed. The **RESO Web API** defines a modern, standardized way to actually pull the data over the internet, replacing older methods.\n\nThe Web API is gradually replacing **RETS legacy**, the older Real Estate Transaction Standard that many MLSs used for years. During this transition, Lofty may connect to some MLSs via the modern Web API and others still on the legacy method, which adds real integration and maintenance overhead."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Why data is still messy",
            "text": "Standards are published, but adoption is uneven. Some MLSs implement the **RESO Data Dictionary** fully, some partially, and some add local custom fields the standard never anticipated. That leftover variation is why Lofty still has to do **data normalization** — cleaning and mapping incoming fields into one consistent internal model.\n\nFor you as a leader, this explains a category of subtle bugs: a filter that works in one market but misbehaves in another often traces back to an MLS whose data doesn't perfectly match the standard, forcing imperfect normalization."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "Why a search filter works in one market but not another",
          "text": "A MidMarket customer reports that filtering by 'waterfront' returns perfect results in one metro but garbage in another, and it lands as an executive escalation. The root cause is usually not Lofty's code — it's that one MLS follows the **RESO Data Dictionary** cleanly while the other uses a local custom field the standard never defined, so **data normalization** has to guess. Knowing this lets you frame the escalation honestly: 'This is an upstream data-standard gap we mitigate, not a simple bug,' and prioritize the normalization fix that helps the most markets at once."
        },
