        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "People do what people around them do",
            "text": "**Social proof** is the tendency to look to others' behavior to decide our own, especially under uncertainty. On a team, the strongest signal of 'how we do things here' is not the policy doc — it's what respected peers are visibly doing. This is why culture spreads sideways faster than it flows down.\n\nFor the teams you influence without owning — the MidMarket Client Success group, a China partner team — this is your highest-leverage tool. You can't mandate their behavior, but you can make the behavior you want **visible** and let peer influence carry it."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Two kinds of norms, and don't mix them up",
            "text": "A **descriptive norm** is what people actually do ('most CSMs log their risk signals'); an **injunctive norm** is what people approve of ('we believe accurate accounts matter'). Behavior follows the descriptive norm far more reliably — people copy actions, not applause.\n\nThe practical rule: when you want more of a behavior, broadcast that many respected peers already do it. When almost no one does it yet, don't announce the low numbers — lead with the approval (injunctive) and the small pockets of adoption instead, until the descriptive norm catches up enough to stand on its own."
          },
          {
            "heading": "The negative norm trap",
            "text": "The most common self-inflicted wound is the **negative norm trap**: loudly complaining about how widespread the bad behavior is. 'Half of you still aren't updating the CRM' is heard as 'lots of my peers skip this, so it must be normal.' You just advertised the behavior you're trying to kill.\n\nFlip it. Spotlight the people doing it right, name them, make their behavior the visible default. Highlighting the minority who comply — not the majority who don't — turns **social proof** from an enemy into an engine."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "Spreading adoption you can't mandate",
          "text": "You want the US MidMarket Client Success team — which you only indirectly oversee — to run structured value recaps before renewals. You can't order it. So you lean on **social proof**. Instead of emailing 'too few of you are doing recaps' (which would broadcast a **negative norm**), you share a short win in the shared channel: a named, respected CSM whose recap saved a wobbly renewal, with her one-page template attached. You're establishing a **descriptive norm** — 'people like us do this, and it works' — and making it **visible** enough that peers copy it. Adoption climbs through **peer influence**, not authority you don't have."
        },
