        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "You get the behavior you reward",
            "text": "An **incentive** is any consequence — money, recognition, status, relief from pain — that makes a behavior more or less likely to recur. The iron rule is that people optimize for what's actually rewarded, not for what you announce you value. If you praise quality but only ever celebrate ticket volume, you'll get volume.\n\nSo before adding an incentive, trace what behavior it truly pays for. The reward doesn't have to be money; on your teams, public recognition, a lighter escalation load, or a visible win in front of peers are often stronger and cheaper than cash."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Perverse incentives and Goodhart's law",
            "text": "A **perverse incentive** rewards a proxy so hard that people game the proxy and abandon the real goal. **Goodhart's law** captures it: when a measure becomes a target, it stops being a good measure. Reward closed-tickets-per-hour and you may get tickets closed fast and badly, or reopened tomorrow.\n\nDefend against this by pairing any speed or volume metric with a counter-metric that catches the gaming — pair close rate with reopen rate, pair refund-avoidance with CSAT. If you can only reward one number, reward an outcome close to the real goal, not a convenient proxy far from it."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Feedback loops and timing",
            "text": "A **feedback loop** tells someone the result of their behavior so they can adjust; behavior that gets no feedback drifts. **Reinforcement timing** matters enormously — feedback that lands close to the behavior shapes it far more than a quarterly review months later. A same-shift 'that de-escalation was textbook' does more than a line in an annual appraisal.\n\nAlso mind **intrinsic vs extrinsic motivation**. Extrinsic rewards work but can crowd out intrinsic drive if overused, turning 'I care about customers' into 'I do it for the bonus.' Use extrinsic rewards to start or spotlight a behavior, then let mastery, autonomy, and purpose sustain it."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "The close-rate that broke quality",
          "text": "To lift your Manila support team's throughput, someone proposes rewarding **tickets closed per agent per shift**. You catch the **perverse incentive**: by **Goodhart's law**, agents will close tickets fast to hit the number, and reopen rates and CSAT will quietly rot. You redesign it. You pair close rate with a **counter-metric** — reopen rate within 72 hours — so gaming shows up immediately. You add a fast **feedback loop**: a short weekly view each agent sees of their own closes-versus-reopens, landing while the work is fresh. And you keep the reward mostly **intrinsic and extrinsic-light** — peer recognition for clean resolutions — so you don't crowd out the pride your best agents already take in the work."
        },
