        "concepts": [
          "Page",
          "Block",
          "Database",
          "Property",
          "Workspace hierarchy"
        ],
        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "Everything is a block",
            "text": "In Notion, the smallest unit of content is a **block** — a paragraph, a heading, a checkbox, a table row. Blocks stack to form a **page**, and pages nest inside other pages to form your **workspace hierarchy**. This is why Notion feels flexible: you rearrange operations documentation by dragging blocks, not by fighting rigid templates.\n\nFor you, running documentation across Manila support, billing, and websites, the takeaway is that structure is cheap to change. You are never locked into a layout, so you can start simple and reshape as your teams' needs evolve."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Pages versus databases",
            "text": "A plain **page** is free-form text — good for a one-off memo or a meeting note. A **database** is a structured collection where every entry is itself a page, and each entry carries the same set of **properties** (status, owner, date, category). The difference matters: a database can be filtered, sorted, and viewed many ways; a plain page cannot.\n\nWhen you want a living list your teams query repeatedly — open escalations, SOPs by team, renewal accounts — you want a database. When you want a static narrative, a page is enough."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Properties give data meaning",
            "text": "A **property** is a typed field attached to every row in a database — text, select, person, date, number, relation. Properties are what let you later say 'show me all SOPs owned by the US billing lead and last reviewed over 90 days ago.' Without properties you have prose; with them you have data your teams can slice."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "Turning a support notes page into a database",
          "text": "Your Manila support team keeps escalation notes as a long plain **page**, and finding last week's billing escalations means scrolling. You convert it into a **database** where each escalation is a row with **properties** for status, owner, customer tier, and date opened. Now the same information can be filtered to 'open, enterprise' in one click — the content did not change, but its structure became queryable for your US global support lead."
        },
        "pauseAndThink": {
          "question": "Why would you choose a database over a plain page for tracking open escalations?",
          "answer": "Because a database gives every escalation the same properties (status, owner, date), which you can filter and sort — a plain page of text can only be scrolled and read."
        },
        "glossary": [
          {
            "term": "Block",
            "definition": "The smallest unit of content in Notion, such as a paragraph, heading, or checkbox."
          },
          {
            "term": "Page",
            "definition": "A stack of blocks that can nest inside other pages to build your workspace."
          },
          {
            "term": "Database",
            "definition": "A structured collection where each entry is a page carrying the same set of properties."
          },
          {
            "term": "Property",
            "definition": "A typed field (status, owner, date, number) attached to every row in a database."
          },
          {
            "term": "Workspace hierarchy",
            "definition": "The nested tree of pages that organizes everything in your Notion workspace."
          }
        ],
        "insights": [
          "Notion's flexibility comes from **blocks** — structure is cheap to rearrange, so start simple.",
          "The line between a note and a tool is **properties**: they turn prose into filterable data.",
          "Choosing a **database** early saves you from rebuilding when a list starts getting queried repeatedly."
        ],
        "action": "Pick one plain-text list your team currently scrolls through and convert it into a **database** with at least three **properties** (status, owner, date).",
