        "sections": [
          {
            "heading": "An SOP is written for a stressed reader",
            "text": "A **standard operating procedure** documents how a recurring task is done — but the test is not completeness, it is usability at the moment of need. Write it scannable: numbered steps, one action per step, the trigger and the owner stated up front. A billing specialist mid-escalation should find the answer in seconds, not read an essay.\n\nKeep each SOP as its own row in an SOP database with properties for team, owner, and last-reviewed date. That way the document is both readable and governable — you can see at a glance which procedures are overdue for review."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Templates make the right way the default",
            "text": "A **database template** pre-fills a new entry with structure — headings, checklists, default property values. When your Manila support team opens a new escalation, the template can already contain the triage steps and the required fields. This makes the correct process the **default**, so people follow it without having to remember it.\n\nDefaults are the quiet lever of operations: the easiest path and the correct path become the same path. **Buttons and automation** extend this — a button can create a pre-templated task or update a status in one click."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Adoption is a design problem, not a discipline problem",
            "text": "Most documentation fails not because it is wrong but because no one uses it. **Adoption** comes from reducing friction: put the SOP where the work happens, keep it short, assign a clear owner, and review it on a cadence so it stays trustworthy. If people find a stale or bloated doc once, they stop trusting all of them.\n\nTreat adoption as something you engineer. Link SOPs directly into the dashboards and templates people already open, so following the process requires no detour."
          }
        ],
        "example": {
          "title": "An escalation SOP that runs itself",
          "text": "You create a **database template** for new escalations that auto-loads a triage checklist, sets status to 'Open', and prompts for customer tier. The **standard operating procedure** for handoff between your Manila support team and your US global support lead lives as a linked, five-step SOP right inside that template. A **button** lets the agent instantly spin up the next-tier task. Because the correct steps are the **default** the moment a ticket opens, **adoption** happens by design — no one has to hunt for the process."
        },
        "pauseAndThink": {
          "question": "Why does putting triage steps inside a database template improve adoption more than writing a separate SOP page?",
          "answer": "Because it makes the correct process the default at the moment work begins — people follow it without a detour or having to remember where the doc lives, so following it requires no extra effort."
        },
