          {
            "heading": "One drag reshapes the whole summary",
            "text": "A **PivotTable** turns a long list into a summary without a single formula. You drop a field into Rows (say, CSM), another into Columns (say, month), and a number into Values, and Excel computes the crosstab instantly. Drag the same field elsewhere and the entire report reshapes.\n\nThis is the fastest way to answer 'how much, by what' questions — tickets by team, revenue by segment, churn by plan — which is exactly the shape of most questions executives ask you on the spot."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Values can count, sum, or average",
            "text": "The **Values** area controls the math. By default Excel sums numbers and counts text, but you can change any field to Count, Average, Max, or Distinct Count. A frequent slip is seeing 'Count of Revenue' when you wanted 'Sum of Revenue' — always check the summary function.\n\nDistinct Count is quietly powerful: it answers 'how many unique accounts' rather than 'how many rows,' which matters when one account has many tickets or line items."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Show Values As turns numbers into shares",
            "text": "Raw totals rarely tell the story; proportions do. The **Show Values As** option recomputes a value field as a percent of the grand total, of the row, or of the column — no extra formula needed. That converts 'Support handled 4,200 tickets' into 'Manila handled 68% of tickets,' which lands far better in a deck.\n\nYou can also show % difference from a prior period, turning a pivot into an instant month-over-month trend view."
          },
          {
            "heading": "Slicers, grouping, and the refresh trap",
            "text": "A **Slicer** is a clickable filter panel: click 'Enterprise' and every connected pivot and chart filters together, which is ideal when you are exploring live in a review. **Grouping** rolls detail up — bucket dates into months or quarters, or group plan tiers — right inside the pivot.\n\nThe one thing everyone forgets: a pivot does not update when its source data changes. You must **Refresh** (right-click, Refresh, or Ctrl+Alt+F5). Stale pivots presenting last week's numbers as this week's is a common and embarrassing error."
          }
